cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Interesting question by Gorrila. The short answer is no, but let me explain. The points are pretty evenly spread  and it is hard to make 2N with 20 or so points between the 2 hands. So tempting as it is to bid, Fred should seriously consider passing. Having said that, my wife had a similar hand several days ago in live bridge, and bid 2N. She could not resist bidding either. However, it did work out badly for us. So, even with a strong balanced hand, when partner is known to be weak, pass should be considered.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now as to the play. The one interesting thing I wish to point out is my low diamond play when I had the Queen and dummy had the Jack. I knew Gorrila could ruff the diamond  but I was hoping Ally had the H10. In this fashion,  I was trying to make it clear to Ally to ruff the diamond, and thus set up my HJ. That play is known as a "Uppercut"  where one defender ruffs high, and promotes a trump in their partner's hand that ordinarily would not win a trick.|
