nt||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's get back to the auction first. South has 16 Starting Points: 15 HCP,  plus 2 length points, and -1 for singleton K (and I will discuss the K further later). Once I raise hearts, he can add 2 for singleton plus 1 for 4+ diamonds for 19  Declarer Points. So, 4H is reasonable. In addition, 5/5 is excellent distribution. On close bids, you should upgrade your hand. same thing for 6-4 which is another reasonably common excellent distribution. If you have 5/5 or 6/4 and are on the borderline, be aggressive. On the other hand if you have a hand with no singletons or voids, be more conservative.|
PG| ***** 92 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, on this hand I would fully discount the CK another point since Fred bid clubs. But I still bid 4H.|
PG| ***** 93 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play. 4H is not makeable if they keep playing clubs. But the right way to play it is to ruff the 2nd club, and play a spade to the King and a heart back. If East ducks, play  the HK and go back to the board with the SA and play another heart. East wins, the heart and plays a black card. you must ruff, and then you only have one trump left. So you play 3 rounds of diamonds, and then if they play another club you are down.|
PG| ***** 94 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I often see inexperienced declarers try and ruff cards in the long hand which usually is not a good idea, as all it does is shorten your trump. This is the way to look at it. If South can manage 1 heart loser, then he has 4 heart winners. And there is no difference between playing your long hearts out and throwing a club as there is in ruffing a club. The only thing ruffing a club does is shorten South's trump which is a disadvantage, not an advantage.|
PG| ***** 95 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So, avoid ruffing in the long hand unless you have a good reason (such as you need an entry, or are trying to set up dummy's long suit). On the other hand, ruffing in the short hand is a very GOOD idea. That creates an extra trick. For example on this hand, if South were able to ruff something in dummy, that would mean 5 heart tricks, 4 long hearts plus the ruff in dummy.|
PG| ***** 96 ***** |


